## How Plugin Architecture Benefits from Lifecycle Management

### Plugin Discovery & Registration
- During initialization, clients discover exactly what plugins are available
- Version compatibility is checked before operations begin
- AI receives a precise inventory of available tools

### Example Plugin Capability Negotiation
```json
// Client initialize request
{
  "protocol": "2024-11-05",
  "capabilities": [
    {"name": "image_generator", "version": "2.1"},
    {"name": "calendar_access", "version": "1.0"},
    {"name": "file_browser", "version": "3.2"}
  ]
}

// Server initialize response
{
  "protocol": "2024-11-05",
  "capabilities": [
    {"name": "calendar_access", "version": "1.0"},
    {"name": "file_browser", "version": "3.0"} // Note: older version
  ]
}
```

### Result: Reliable Plugin Operation
- AI only attempts to use plugins it knows are available
- Clear boundaries prevent feature guessing
- Explicit version handling prevents compatibility issues

## Tool Definition Anatomy

### How Tools Are Defined for AI Systems

```json
{
  "name": "get_weather",
  "description": "Gets current weather for a location. Use when user asks about weather.",
  "parameters": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "location": {
        "type": "string",
        "description": "The city and state/country"
      },
      "unit": {
        "type": "string",
        "enum": ["celsius", "fahrenheit"],
        "default": "celsius"
      }
    },
    "required": ["location"]
  }
}
```

### Key Components
- **Name**: Unique identifier for the tool
- **Description**: Explains what the tool does and when to use it
- **Parameters**: Schema defining inputs the tool needs
    - Property types and constraints
    - Which parameters are required vs. optional
    - Default values for optional parameters

The AI uses the description to understand when to use the tool and the schema to know what parameters to provide.

## Implementing Prompts in an MCP Server

### 1. Declare Prompt Support in Server Capabilities
```json
{
  "capabilities": {
    "prompts": true,
    "other_feature": "value"
  }
}
```

### 2. Set Up Handler for prompts/list Endpoint
```python
@app.route('/mcp/prompts/list')
def handle_prompts_list():
    # Define available prompts
    available_prompts = [
        {
            "name": "code_review",
            "description": "Reviews code for best practices and bugs",
            "arguments": [
                {
                    "name": "code",
                    "type": "string",
                    "description": "The code to be reviewed",
                    "required": True
                },
                {
                    "name": "language",
                    "type": "string",
                    "description": "Programming language of the code",
                    "required": False
                }
            ]
        }
        # Additional prompts would be listed here
    ]

    # Return the prompt definitions
    return {"prompts": available_prompts}
```

### 3. Implement prompts/get Handler
```python
@app.route('/mcp/prompts/get')
def handle_prompts_get():
    # Extract prompt name and arguments from request
    prompt_name = request.json["name"]
    arguments = request.json["arguments"]

    # Format the appropriate prompt template
    if prompt_name == "code_review":
        code = arguments["code"]
        language = arguments.get("language", "")

        # Return formatted messages for the LLM
        return {
            "messages": [
                {
                    "role": "user",
                    "content": f"Please review this code{' in ' + language if language else ''}:\n\n```\n{code}\n```"
                }
            ]
        }

    # Handle other prompt types...
```

